# JavaScript Debounce Function

Debouncing prevents a function from being called too frequently by delaying its execution until after a specified wait time has passed since the last call.

```javascript
function debounce(func, wait) {
  let timeout;
  return function(...args) {
    clearTimeout(timeout);
    timeout = setTimeout(() => func.apply(this, args), wait);
  };
}

// Example usage
const debouncedSearch = debounce((query) => {
  console.log(`Searching for: ${query}`);
}, 300);

// Will only log "Searching for: test" after 300ms of no additional calls
debouncedSearch('t');
debouncedSearch('te');
debouncedSearch('tes');
debouncedSearch('test');
```

The `debounce` function returns a new function that, when called repeatedly, will only execute once after the specified delay (300ms in the example) if no additional calls are made.
